The Wild
Cards
--------

Not surprisingly, succession looms as a larger problem for the
three firms where the issue has gone unresolved for years: JPMorgan Chase, =
led by Dimon for some 20 years; Bank of America, led by Brian Moynihan, who=
=E2=80=99s been the bank=E2=80=99s C.E.O. for a little more than 15 years; =
and BlackRock, where 72-year-old Larry Fink can=E2=80=99t seem to keep a su=
ccessor. Last week, Mark Wiedman, the third potential successor to Fink, le=
ft the firm unexpectedly, following the departures of Salim
Ramji, now C.E.O. of Vanguard, and Mark Wiseman, now chairman of Lazard=E2=
=80=99s business in Canada.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The trouble is also particularly acute at BofA and JPM, where neither Moyni=
han nor Dimon seem keen on giving up their roles. Moynihan, for one, has ma=
de clear he=E2=80=99s not going anywhere. At 64, he=E2=80=99s said he=E2=80=
=99ll stay at the bank until at least the end of the decade. I couldn=E2=80=
=99t begin to
tell you who=E2=80=99s in line to succeed him, and neither can anyone else,=
 I=E2=80=99d wager. There=E2=80=99s an array of possible internal candidate=
s, none of whom are obvious or well-known. Nonetheless, Moynihan avers that=
 he has a plan for succession, should one be needed before the end of the d=
ecade, or whenever he chooses to hang up his cleats.

=C2=A0

Dimon, too, seems determined not to abdicate for the foreseeable
future, or until the end of time, whichever comes first. JPMorgan Chase, wh=
ich has a market value of $740 billion thanks in large part to Dimon=E2=80=
=99s 20 years at the helm, recently announced a series of management change=
s that did absolutely nothing to clarify who would succeed King Jamie. Dani=
el Pinto, who stepped in for Dimon during his health scare and is the firm=
=E2=80=99s president and chief operating officer, will leave the bank at th=
e end of 2026. This June 30, he=E2=80=99ll relinquish his
titles and become a vice chairman and senior banker advising clients.

=C2=A0

Jamie=E2=80=99s reluctance to retire seems to have unsettled other successi=
on contingencies, too. Jennifer Piepszak, who had been co-leader of the ban=
k=E2=80=99s corporate and investment bank, was named chief operating office=
r, effective immediately, under Pinto=E2=80=99s guidance until he leaves th=
e role in June. You=E2=80=99d think the promotion
positions the well-liked Piepszak to succeed Dimon, but you=E2=80=99d be wr=
ong. At the time of her promotion, a bank spokesman announced that Piepszak=
 took herself out of the running to succeed Dimon. =E2=80=9CPiepszak has ma=
de clear her preference for a senior operating role, working closely with J=
amie and in support of the top leadership and she doesn=E2=80=99t want to b=
e considered for the C.E.O. position at this time,=E2=80=9D the spokesman s=
aid.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

All of which makes murkier the question of who in the world can succeed Jam=
ie. There=E2=80=99s a roster of internal candidates=E2=80=94Marianne Lake, =
Mary Erdoes, Doug Petno, and Troy Rohrbaugh=E2=80=94all of whom report dire=
ctly to Jamie, but none of whom, in my humble opinion, have the gravitas to=
 fill the shoes of one of America=E2=80=99s greatest bankers ever. I suspec=
t JPMorgan Chase might end up doing what it
did when they hired Jamie: find someone to run the place who=E2=80=99s neve=
r worked there.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

You=E2=80=99ll recall that Jamie was C.E.O. of Bank One when JPMorgan Chase=
 acquired it for $58 billion in 2004. The Federal Reserve hasn=E2=80=99t al=
lowed bank mergers of that size since the 2008 financial crisis, and especi=
ally not by our SIFIs=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Csystemically important financial ins=
titutions.=E2=80=9D That might change during Trump II, if
Jay Powell=E2=80=99s term as Fed chief ends next year. Trump might be willi=
ng=E2=80=94eager, in fact=E2=80=94to appoint a Fed chairman who=E2=80=99d u=
nleash the big U.S. banks to do material M&A deals once again, which could =
in turn position Jamie to pull a Bill Harrison and acquihire his successor.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

If that doesn=E2=80=99t work, or isn=E2=80=99t permitted, there are plenty =
of bankers out there with the stature to follow Jamie as
C.E.O. of our largest and most profitable bank=E2=80=942024 net income, $52=
 billion. The bigger question is when Jamie will admit it=E2=80=99s time.

