strong><span style=3D"word-break:break-word;background-color:transparent;">=
 and </span><strong style=3D"background-color:transparent;">Guzel Ganieva</=
strong><span style=3D"word-break:break-word;background-color:transparent;">=
,
a Russian woman with whom he=E2=80=99d had a consensual affair.=C2=A0</span=
></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">Since Marc took charge of the firm, the stock is up 2=
53 percent, and Apollo=E2=80=99s market value is now $100 billion. Marc is =
kind of a cheap date for Apollo: He only takes a salary of $100,000 to run =
the firm, plus expenses related to his job, including getting reimbursed fo=
r the use of his own private jet when he=E2=80=99s traveling on business. H=
e
also gets carried interest in the firm=E2=80=99s various funds and, of cour=
se, his 58 million Apollo shares are currently worth nearly $10 billion. (A=
t press time, I was still waiting to hear back whether this remains his dea=
l with the new contract, but let=E2=80=99s assume so until I hear different=
ly.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Like Goldman, Apollo seems to have locked in its l=
eader for the intermediate term. If Rowan gives up the post when his
five-year contract runs out, his successor will be 62-year-old <strong>Jim =
Zelter</strong>, who=E2=80=99s just been promoted to president of the firm,=
 overseeing Apollo=E2=80=99s roughly $750 billion of assets, including priv=
ate equity, private credit, and its annuity insurance business, Athene. Zel=
ter, who roomed with NBA commissioner <strong>Adam Silver </strong>at Duke,=
 has been at Apollo since 2006, and was previously co-president of Apollo=
=E2=80=99s asset management business. Other candidates to succeed Rowan
include <strong>Scott Kleinman</strong>, 52, and <strong>John Zito</strong>=
, 43, who together will now run Apollo=E2=80=99s asset management business.=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;">Obviously, if Rowan <em>were</em> to take a job in Washington, Zelter wo=
uld be Apollo=E2=80=99s next C.E.O. But if Rowan sticks around, the Apollo =
board, which is looking for a new chairman, given the impending departure o=
f <strong>Jay Clayton</strong> to become the U.S. Attorney for the
Southern District of New York, might choose one of the two younger men to b=
e Apollo=E2=80=99s C.E.O. In any event, like Goldman, Apollo seems to have =
answered the question of near-term succession.</p></div>
