=3D"margin:0;">So where on Wall Street does succession remain an open quest=
ion? Not at Morgan
Stanley, where <strong>James Gorman</strong>=E2=80=94now leading the charge=
 at Disney to find <strong>Bob Iger</strong>=E2=80=99s successor=E2=80=94ra=
n an elegant process and chose <strong>Ted Pick </strong>to follow him. A w=
ise choice, it seems, as Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s stock is up 61 percent in=
 the year since Pick succeeded Gorman. Likewise, succession questions at th=
e Carlyle Group seem to have settled down after they lured <strong>Harvey S=
chwartz</strong>=E2=80=94lost out to Solomon for the top job at Goldman=E2=
=80=94with the promise
of something like $187 million in compensation. This hire, too, seems to be=
 paying off: Carlyle=E2=80=99s stock is up 50 percent since Schwartz took o=
ver in February 2023, although it still lags its rivals in market value and=
 influence.</p></div>
