bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Not surprisingly, succession looms as a larger =
problem for the
three firms where the issue has gone unresolved for years: JPMorgan Chase, =
led by Dimon for some 20 years; Bank of America, led by <strong>Brian Moyni=
han,</strong> who=E2=80=99s been the bank=E2=80=99s C.E.O. for a little mor=
e than 15 years; and BlackRock, where 72-year-old <strong>Larry Fink </stro=
ng>can=E2=80=99t seem to <em>keep</em> a successor. Last week, <strong>Mark=
 Wiedman</strong>, the <em>third</em> potential successor to Fink, left the=
 firm unexpectedly, following the departures of <strong>Salim
Ramji</strong>, now C.E.O. of Vanguard, and <strong>Mark Wiseman</strong>, =
now chairman of Lazard=E2=80=99s business in Canada.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">The trouble is also particularly acute at BofA and JPM, where neither M=
oynihan nor Dimon seem keen on giving up their roles. Moynihan, for one, ha=
s made clear he=E2=80=99s not going anywhere. At 64, he=E2=80=99s said he=
=E2=80=99ll stay at the bank until at least the end of the decade. I couldn=
=E2=80=99t begin to
tell you who=E2=80=99s in line to succeed him, and neither can anyone else,=
 I=E2=80=99d wager. There=E2=80=99s an array of possible internal candidate=
s, none of whom are obvious or well-known. Nonetheless, Moynihan avers that=
 he <em>has</em> a plan for succession, should one be needed before the end=
 of the decade, or whenever he chooses to hang up his cleats.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Dimon, too, seems determined not to abdicate for the foreseeable
future, or until the end of time, whichever comes first. JPMorgan Chase, wh=
ich has a market value of $740 billion thanks in large part to Dimon=E2=80=
=99s 20 years at the helm, recently announced a series of management change=
s that did absolutely nothing to clarify who would succeed King Jamie. <str=
ong>Daniel Pinto</strong>, who stepped in for Dimon during his health scare=
 and is the firm=E2=80=99s president and chief operating officer, will leav=
e the bank at the end of 2026. This June 30, he=E2=80=99ll relinquish his
titles and become a vice chairman and senior banker advising clients.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">Jamie=E2=80=99s reluctance to retire seems to have unsettled=
 other succession contingencies, too. <strong>Jennifer Piepszak</strong>, w=
ho had been co-leader of the bank=E2=80=99s corporate and investment bank, =
was named chief operating officer, effective immediately, under Pinto=E2=80=
=99s guidance until he leaves the role in June. You=E2=80=99d think the pro=
motion
positions the well-liked Piepszak to succeed Dimon, but you=E2=80=99d be wr=
ong. At the time of her promotion, a bank spokesman announced that Piepszak=
 took herself <em>out</em> of the running to succeed Dimon. =E2=80=9CPiepsz=
ak has made clear her preference for a senior operating role, working close=
ly with Jamie and in support of the top leadership and she doesn=E2=80=99t =
want to be considered for the C.E.O. position at this time,=E2=80=9D the sp=
okesman said.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">All of which makes murkier the ques=
tion of who in the world can succeed Jamie. There=E2=80=99s a roster of int=
ernal candidates=E2=80=94<strong>Marianne Lake</strong>, <strong>Mary Erdoe=
s</strong>, <strong>Doug Petno</strong>, and<strong> Troy Rohrbaugh</strong=
>=E2=80=94all of whom report directly to Jamie, but none of whom, in my hum=
ble opinion, have the <em>gravitas</em> to fill the shoes of one of America=
=E2=80=99s greatest bankers ever. I suspect JPMorgan Chase might end up doi=
ng what it
did when they hired Jamie: find someone to run the place who=E2=80=99s neve=
r worked there.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">You=E2=80=99ll recall that Jamie =
was C.E.O. of Bank One when JPMorgan Chase acquired it for $58 billion in 2=
004. The Federal Reserve hasn=E2=80=99t allowed bank mergers of that size s=
ince the 2008 financial crisis, and especially not by our SIFIs=E2=80=94=E2=
=80=9Csystemically important financial institutions.=E2=80=9D That might ch=
ange during Trump II, if
<strong>Jay Powell</strong>=E2=80=99s term as Fed chief ends next year. Tru=
mp might be willing=E2=80=94eager, in fact=E2=80=94to appoint a Fed chairma=
n who=E2=80=99d unleash the big U.S. banks to do material M&amp;A deals onc=
e again, which could in turn position Jamie to pull a <strong>Bill Harrison=
</strong> and acquihire his successor.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">If that doesn=E2=80=99t work=
, or isn=E2=80=99t permitted, there are plenty of bankers out there with th=
e stature to follow Jamie as
C.E.O. of our largest and most profitable bank=E2=80=942024 net income, $52=
 billion. The bigger question is when Jamie will admit it=E2=80=99s time.</=
p></div>
